</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 SIMPLE PASSION by Annie Ernaux, translated from the French by Tanya Leslie 
(Ballantine: $8.50; 64 pp.) . A bestseller in France, Annie Ernaux's novella 
explores the emotions of a sophisticated woman involved with a married man. The 
unnamed narrator savors her passion, but never loses sight of its transitory 
nature: "From the very beginning, and throughout the whole of our affair, I had 
the privilege of knowing what we all find out in the end: the man we love is a 
complete stranger." This elegantly Gallic reflection on the nature of love 
suggests an upper-class restatement of Edith Piaf's "No, Je ne regrette rien."  
</P>
</TEXT>
