<HEADLINE>
<P>
PALM LATITUDES: L.A. SPEAK; L.A. COUNTY JAIL JARGON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Sondra Ferrell 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 all day: n. a life sentence. "I can't believe it! Nobody gets all day for a 
drive-by anymore!" 
</P>
<P>
 catching the chain: v. leaving County Jail for a state penitentiary. 
</P>
<P>
 criminally challenged: adj. the politically correct term for inmates/convicts. 
SENTENCE? 
</P>
<P>
 dump truck: n. defense attorney who, in the inmate's opinion, did a lousy job. 
"My attorney is such a dump truck, that bells ring when he backs up." 
</P>
<P>
 green room: n. the gas chamber at San Quentin. 
</P>
<P>
 gray goose: n. a bus used to transport inmates from county jails to the state 
prisons. "I can't wait to catch the grey goose and get out of this county 
dump." 
</P>
<P>
 house: n. cell. "It's almost 3 o'clock, I'd better clean my house before 
chow." 
</P>
<P>
 pruno: n. inmate-manufactured alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
 racking the gate: v. opening the cell doors. 
</P>
<P>
 toss up: n. a cell search.  
</P>
<P>
 Thomas Wolfe: n. a lifer. from "You Can't Go Home Again." Sondra Ferrell 
</P>
</TEXT>
