<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'THE JOY LUCK CLUB' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In an age of contrived sentimentality, director Wayne Wang and Amy Tan's 1993 
film from Tan's best-selling novel offers deeply felt, straight-from-the-heart 
emotions.A story of distance and how to bridge it, of painful gaps between 
immigrant mothers and U.S.-born children, it has the strength and clarity of 
its source. While their names are largely unfamiliar to general audiences, the 
eight actresses who play the film's four pairs of mothers and daughters are not 
only the pick of several generations of acting talent but also women who 
understand these characters from the inside out. Pictured here is France Nuyen 
comforting Lauren Tom (Showtime Saturday at 10:30 p.m.). Kenneth Turan 
</P>
