<HEADLINE>
<P>
GIRL, 6, HIT BY CAR, CRITICALLY HURT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 6-year-old girl was struck and critically injured by a car Saturday morning 
as she tried to cross the street in a quiet residential neighborhood, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 The girl was attempting to cross the street about 9 a.m. in the 10400 block of 
Debra Avenue when she was struck by a Nissan Maxima driven by Rozik Nazarian, 
52, of Granada Hills. 
</P>
<P>
 The injured girl's 8-year-old brother watched from the sidewalk, police said. 
Police did not know whether the children were being supervised by an adult at 
the time. 
</P>
<P>
 The girl, whom police declined to identify, was flown to Children's Hospital 
in Hollywood and was in critical condition on a life-support system, a nursing 
supervisor said. Police said the child suffered severe head injuries. 
</P>
<P>
 "The girl crossed the street mid-block," said Los Angeles Police Sgt. Ben Lee. 
"The driver said she didn't see her until it was too late."  
</P>
<P>
 Witnesses said Nazarian was driving about 45 m.p.h., a speed that is not 
considered reckless, police said. Nazarian was not arrested, but the 
investigation will continue, Lee said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
