<HEADLINE>
<P>
KEEP LAUSD OUT OF WELL-RUN PARENT CENTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * I thought the article by Beth Shuster, "Unwelcome Support for Parent 
Centers" (Aug. 24), was well-written and told the LAUSD what they need to hear 
-- if they will listen. There already exists on LAUSD campuses help for people 
who know how to use the system.What the Parent Centers offer is a 
non-threatening way to introduce to the campus parents who might otherwise be 
intimidated by the system. Once they feel comfortable on the campus, they can 
avail themselves of the resources the school has to offer. If necessary, parent 
leaders can shepherd them through the system. 
</P>
<P>
 What is not needed is another layer of LAUSD bureaucracy, no matter how well 
meaning, to intimidate parents who are making their first steps toward relating 
to a system that in most cases is overwhelming. If the LAUSD wants to get 
involved with parents, it should support things like the PTA, which is for 
parents who want to get involved by interacting with teachers and the school 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
 The Parent Centers fulfill a different purpose -- namely providing a buffer or 
sometimes an acting as an ombudsman between parents and the school. Making it 
an LAUSD-run program defeats its whole purpose. 
</P>
<P>
 DAN STEWART 
</P>
<P>
 Sherman Oaks 
</P>
</TEXT>
