<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEAN HELPS FLORIDA MAKE A CASE, 73-7; SEC: QUARTERBACK HAS FOUR TOUCHDOWN 
PASSES FOR NO. 2-RANKED GATORS IN ROUT OF KENTUCKY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Coach Steve Spurrier of No. 2-ranked Florida isn't eager to join a debate over 
who should be No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
 Although the Gators made a powerful statement for returning to the top spot 
with a 73-7 Southeastern Conference victory over Kentucky on Saturday, Spurrier 
said he's more concerned about next week's game at Tennessee than with the 
polls. 
</P>
<P>
 "Seriously, Nebraska deserved to be up there as much as we did," said 
Spurrier, whose team slipped behind the Cornhuskers last week despite beating 
New Mexico State by 49 points in its first game. 
</P>
<P>
 "We were honored to be up there in the preseason, but we really hadn't done 
all that much. We won one game we should have won. . . . We'll be tested a lot 
more when we play Tennessee." 
</P>
<P>
 The Gators, who needed a last-minute touchdown to beat the Wildcats a year 
ago, scored on five of their first six possessions en route to a 31-7 halftime 
lead on Saturday. They improved to 2-0 overall and 1-0 in the SEC. 
</P>
<P>
 Last September at Lexington, Ky., Terry Dean had four passes intercepted and 
was yanked twice before backup Danny Wuerffel rescued the Gators. This time, 
Dean was nearly flawless. 
</P>
<P>
 After tying an NCAA record with seven touchdown passes in the first half of 
Florida's 70-21 victory over New Mexico State, Dean had four more against 
Kentucky (1-1, 0-1), which trailed, 21-0, before it managed to make a first 
down. 
</P>
<P>
 Dean left the game late in the third quarter, finishing with 15 completions in 
22 attempts for 201 yards. In five quarters this season, he has 11 touchdown 
passes and no interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
 After Dean tossed a perfect spiral to Reidel Anthony on a 65-yard scoring play 
in the third quarter, the Florida Field crowd of 85,238 began to chant "We're 
No. 1!" 
</P>
<P>
 The roar continued when Xavier McCray picked up Daymon Carter's fumble on the 
ensuing kickoff and ran it back 33 yards for a 52-7 lead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
