<HEADLINE>
<P>
MCCALLUM PAYS A VISIT TO TEAMMATES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE SPRINGER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Napoleon McCallum returned to the Raiders on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 Five days after suffering a season-ending, career-threatening leg injury, 
McCallum showed up at the Raiders' El Segundo headquarters in a wheelchair to 
visit his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm all right," the fullback said. "I just came by to say hi and tell 
everybody I'm fine." 
</P>
<P>
 McCallum ruptured an artery in his left leg and dislocated his kneecap on a 
tackle by San Francisco linebacker Ken Norton in Monday night's Raider-49er 
game. 
</P>
<P>
 Drawing on his deep religious faith and his unwavering optimism, McCallum is 
ready to deal with his uncertain future. But he's not ready to talk about the 
past. 
</P>
<P>
 Asked about the injury, McCallum paused, then said, "I knew something was bad, 
but I don't want to relive it or have to read about it." 
</P>
<P>
 Because the play occurred on national television, McCallum has received a 
tremendous outpouring of concern and sympathy from fans. 
</P>
<P>
 "Some of the things I've heard have been really touching," he said. "But I'm 
not ready to get sentimental. I just want to get right, get ready and get 
fixed. 
</P>
<P>
 "I know the Lord has got something for me, has got a plan, and I'm just 
following it the best I can." STEVE SPRINGER 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091194-0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 078204 </DOCID>
