<HEADLINE>
<P>
CD SPOTLIGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Richard Cromelin 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ** 1/2; VARIOUS ARTISTS, "Red Hot + Country" ( Mercury ) 
</P>
<P>
 The fourth entry in the "Red Hot" series of AIDS benefit albums is a sort of 
square-dance mosh pit, with a colliding cast of commercial hotshots (Billy Ray 
Cyrus, Brooks & Dunn), all-timers (Johnny Cash, Dolly Parton), cult figures 
(Jimmie Dale Gilmore, Nanci Griffith) and sub-cult names (Wilco, the successor 
of the admired indie duo Uncle Tupelo). 
</P>
<P>
 While inconsistent, the album keeps coming through with memorable moments, 
such as Gilmore's outing with Willie Nelson on the latter's "Crazy," and Carl 
Perkins' collaboration with the Mavericks and Duane Eddy on a rambunctious 
"Matchbox." The most notable comments on AIDS: Project spearhead Kathy Mattea's 
duet with Jackson Browne on his "Rock Me on the Water," and Mary Chapin 
Carpenter's reading of John Jennings' "Willie Short." Richard Cromelin 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Recording Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
