<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS / ALLAN SLOAN: INSIGHT; PLAN TO REGAIN CONTROL OF BANKRUPT COMPANY IS 
CLASSIC VICTOR POSNER PLOY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN SLOAN, ALLAN SLOAN is a financial columnist for Newsday in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Victor Posner is proof that you can't keep a bad man down. 
</P>
<P>
 Today's example involves NVF Co., the once-proud plastics and fiber 
manufacturer that staggered into bankruptcy last year after decades of 
plundering by Posner. Now, having gutted NVF, Posner is trying to pervert the 
bankruptcy process to settle NVF's debts at a discount, snatch the company away 
from the creditors who aren't part of his game, and at the same time get an 
ultra-cheap release from a dandy lawsuit NVF's public bondholders filed against 
him in June.  
</P>
<P>
 The suit, a classic, lays out in telling detail how Posner diverted millions 
to himself through excessive salaries and perks, and how he siphoned additional 
millions to support the rest of his now-collapsed empire. Posner, who has a 
huge private fortune, proposes to settle the suit for $4 million, which is a 
joke. "This plan gives Posner the whole upside, and releases him from our claim 
of $180 million or more," said Joanne Wills, the creditors' lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
 Also named in the suit is American Financial Corp., run by old-time corporate 
raider Carl Lindner. Profiting from Posner's pain, American Financial and some 
of its executives cut sweet deals for financing Posner. They and Posner would 
own the post-bankruptcy NVF. Think of the Lindnerites as piranhas stripping 
flesh from a drowning man. 
</P>
<P>
 Posner is even trying to use the bankruptcy process to end-run federal 
regulators. This plan would make NVF a private company, freeing Posner to 
control it again. Posner was forced out of NVF, whose stock and bonds are 
publicly traded, because of the marvelous decision last year by U.S. District 
Judge Milton Pollack granting the Securities and Exchange Commission's request 
to bar Posner from influencing any public company. 
</P>
<P>
 Under this plan, there would be no public NVF securities, so Posner could 
retake control. I keep calling it Posner's plan, even though it's being 
submitted by NVF rather than by Posner. Under bankruptcy law, only NVF can file 
a plan as things stand now.  
</P>
<P>
 Pollack was too smart to let me draw him into a conversation about whether 
Posner's converting NVF to a private company from a public company is covered 
by his decision. Pollack referred me to George Heyman Jr., whom he appointed as 
trustee for Posner's stakes in public companies. Heyman, who hasn't been active 
in the NVF bankruptcy, didn't return my call. 
</P>
<P>
 Barry Goldsmith, the SEC lawyer who led the charge against Posner, said in an 
interview that Posner's NVF maneuverings aren't covered by Pollack's order as 
long as Posner doesn't control NVF. The fact that Posner's old, handpicked 
board controls NVF doesn't seem to count. 
</P>
<P>
 Goldsmith said if Posner's plan gets the necessary approvals from creditors, 
the SEC, which is a party in the case, will ask the bankruptcy judge to refuse 
to approve the plan because of Posner's long history of financial misdeeds.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Wonderful. But likely to be too late. Stopping a bankruptcy reorganization at 
that point is like stepping onto railroad tracks to stop a locomotive. You're 
much more likely to get splattered all over the landscape than to stop the 
train. 
</P>
<P>
 The plan submitted by the Posner-picked NVF board is cleverly drawn. Even 
though the public bondholders, with $60 million of claims, are suing Posner and 
fighting him tooth and nail, the plan is structured so that two 
Lindner-controlled classes, totaling $10 million of secured NVF bonds, can 
force the plan down the public bondholders' throats. It's too complicated to 
explain; just trust me. 
</P>
<P>
 Why would NVF's directors be supporting this outrage -- especially when 
there's an alternative plan that offers everyone but Lindner and Posner a 
better deal? 
</P>
<P>
 Maybe it's because even though Posner is gone, his board remains. Or because 
those board members will be released from the bondholders' lawsuit if Posner's 
plan is approved, but will still be liable if it's not. In any event, the 
company's attorney did not respond to my questions. 
</P>
<P>
 And guess what? According to Mark Feldman, an adviser to NVF's public 
bondholders (and, you should know, a friend of mine), Posner is being 
represented by Donald Glazer, a long-time associate. Feldman says Glazer 
advised NVF early in the bankruptcy, then changed clients. Funny how that 
works. I can't give you Glazer's side, because he wouldn't talk to me. 
</P>
<P>
 Which brings us to Posner's rival for NVF -- Richard Beltzhoover, an 
Indianapolis insulation salesman. 
</P>
<P>
 Beltzhoover, 56, says he's been selling NVF's vulcanized fiber for 24 years, 
the last 20 of them through his company, Insulation Representatives. 
Beltzhoover said he's afraid NVF will go out of business if Posner regains 
control and resumes looting. 
</P>
<P>
 "I decided to put my mouth where my money is," Beltzhoover said in an 
interview. "I'm very interested in keeping this company alive."  
</P>
<P>
 Despite his aw-shucks affectations, Beltzhoover put together an investor 
group, and has just reduced his offer to NVF's bondholders, though it's still 
better than Posner's. In any event, Beltzhoover is way behind in the 
maneuvering, and can't catch up unless Posner's plan is tossed out. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 There's a hearing scheduled this week on whether to release the Posner -- 
oops, NVF -- plan so creditors can vote on it. The plan allows someone to top 
Posner's bid, but the terms are stacked in Posner's favor. Not nice, but 
clever. 
</P>
<P>
 Posner, 76, is said to be still recovering from the ruptured aorta he suffered 
in July. But as NVF shows, whatever ails Posner, it's certainly not a shortage 
of gall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
